16. So much of Salus Populi : now of Suprema Lex.

This expression, “ The Supreme Law,'’ supposes that there must somewhere in a State reside a Power which is to provide for emergen- cies for which Law does not provide. And that it does not, is no fault either of the Law or of the Legislator, but arises from the nature of the things with which Law is concerned. For these things are too indefinite and various to be comprehended always in definite and fixed Rules.
